# TouchWeather — Friction Log

Notes from building a Pebble watchapp targeting **emery** (Pebble Time 2, 200×228 rect)
and **gabbro** (Pebble Round 2, 260×260 round) with the 2026 Pebble SDK.
Captured for future Pebble projects so we don't relearn the same lessons.

---

## SDK / toolchain

- **Active SDK matters.** `pebble --version` shows `(active SDK: vX)`. Switch with
  `pebble sdk activate <version>`. Always check before debugging "missing API"
  errors — older SDKs silently lack newer headers (e.g. `touch_service_*`
  appeared in 4.9.169 for gabbro).
- **Touch API is gabbro-only**, not in the basalt/aplite/emery headers. Guard
  with `#if defined(PBL_TOUCH)`. The signature is:
  ```c
  typedef struct TouchEvent { TouchEventType type:8; int16_t x; int16_t y; } TouchEvent;
  void touch_service_subscribe(TouchServiceHandler handler, void *context);
  // handler is: void (*)(const TouchEvent *event, void *context)
  ```
  Older docs reference `TouchEventInfo` / `event.position` — those don't exist.
- **UPDATE (SDK 4.9.169, May 2026):** the "gabbro-only" claim above is no
  longer true. Both **emery** and **gabbro** ship real `touch_service_*`
  prototypes in their `pebble.h` and define `PBL_TOUCH` at build time
  (`flint` does too). Aplite/basalt/chalk/diorite still stub the calls
  to `(0)`. So `#if defined(PBL_TOUCH)` is still the right guard, it just
  enables more platforms now. Pull-down gestures, taps, etc. work on
  Pebble Time 2 hardware.
- `TouchEventType` has only 3 members: `TouchEvent_Touchdown`,
  `TouchEvent_Liftoff`, `TouchEvent_PositionUpdate`. There is no
  higher-level swipe/drag recognizer — implement gestures yourself by
  tracking dx/dy from Touchdown to Liftoff.
- **Find the real types:** `~/Library/Application Support/Pebble SDK/SDKs/current/sdk-core/pebble/<platform>/include/pebble.h`
  is the source of truth. Grep it before guessing.
- **`pebble emu-app-config`** throws a Python traceback in pebble-tool 5.0.34.
  Test config flow on hardware, or via `Pebble.openURL(clay.generateUrl())` in a
  browser dev-tools session against `http://localhost:62604`.

## Emulator quirks (the hours-eater)

- **`pebble install --emulator <plat>` will hang indefinitely** if the emulator
  process gets orphaned by a parent shell exit. Symptom: `libpebble2.exceptions.TimeoutError`
  or `ConnectionResetError [Errno 54]` on the next command.
- **Fix:** start the emulator detached so it survives:
  ```bash
  nohup pebble install --emulator gabbro > /tmp/install.log 2>&1 &
  disown
  ```
  Then run screenshots / button presses normally. Don't background-and-wait
  inside an interactive `&&` chain — the websocket dies when the foreground
  command finishes.
- **Hard kill when stuck:** `pebble kill` is unreliable. Use:
  ```bash
  pkill -9 -f qemu-pebble; pkill -9 -f pypkjs; pkill -f "pebble install"
  ```
- **macOS doesn't ship `timeout(1)`.** Use `(cmd & PID=$!; sleep N; kill -0 $PID && kill -9 $PID)`
  pattern instead.
- **Screenshots:** `pebble screenshot --no-open` avoids opening Preview every
  time. `--vnc` is only needed in headless Linux/CI.
- **Headless guidance from CLAUDE.md** about `--vnc` does **not** apply to
  macOS desktop runs. Skip it locally.
- **Real device is often faster than the emulator for iteration.** Use:
  ```bash
  pebble build && pebble install --phone 192.168.86.33
  ```
  Connects over local WiFi (phone and watch must both be on same network). Much
  more reliable than the emulator for touch, Clay config, and theme flows that
  are impossible to test in `qemu-pebble`. Clay round-trip in particular
  requires real hardware — `pebble emu-app-config` throws a Python traceback.
- **Emulator button ordering for navigation testing:** `click down` advances to
  the next card (DOWN navigates forward), `click up` goes back. SELECT toggles
  whatever you've wired it to (we use it for theme). Script all 5 screenshots
  in one shell pipeline after install.

## Graphics / drawing

- **Round vs rectangular** is huge. Always use `PBL_IF_ROUND_ELSE(round, rect)`
  for y-positions of headers, banners, and bottom rows. The page indicator
  needs to sit above the bezel curve — `y = 224` works on gabbro (260px tall).
- **`graphics_fill_radial`** is the right tool for half-discs and arc gauges:
  ```c
  graphics_fill_radial(ctx, rect, GOvalScaleModeFitCircle, thickness,
                       DEG_TO_TRIGANGLE(-90), DEG_TO_TRIGANGLE(90));
  ```
  Don't try to draw arcs by lots of `graphics_draw_line` segments — slow and
  ugly. Use `DEG_TO_TRIGANGLE`, not raw `TRIG_MAX_ANGLE` math, for arc bounds.
- **`graphics_fill_circle` ≠ half-circle.** For sunrise/sunset, mask with
  `graphics_fill_radial` from -90° to +90° instead of clipping rects.
- **`set_stroke_width`** persists across draw calls. Reset it at the top of
  each icon function or you'll get random thick lines later.
- **Antialiasing:** call `graphics_context_set_antialiased(ctx, true);` once.
  Big difference on circles and rays.
- **Drawing arrows:** "vertical shaft + chevron arms from the tip". Naive
  3-line "Y" shapes look wrong — confirm both lines start at the *tip*, not
  the center.
- **`GColorChromeYellow` ≈ #FFAA00** (Pebble orange). `GColorVividCerulean` ≈
  #00AAFF (Pebble blue). These are the canonical accent colors for the 2026
  design language. The 64-color palette is severely limited; pick from
  https://developer.repebble.com/guides/tools-and-resources/color-picker before
  guessing color names.
- **Half-radial gauge pattern (UV / AQI):** same code, just change the input
  range. UV: 0–16 → 0°–180°. AQI: 0–300 → 0°–180°. Center the containing
  rect so the flat edge of the half-disc sits on a horizontal baseline — users
  read it like a speedometer. A filled `thickness=10` ring is more legible than
  a thin stroke.
- **Bar charts with zero-value columns:** don't draw a full-height empty bar
  and don't silently skip the column. Draw a short muted baseline stroke (2px)
  so the column position is still visible, then draw the real fill only when
  `pct > 0`. This avoids the "missing bars" bug that comes from applying a
  minimum-height floor to all bars (the floor creates phantom bars at zero).
- **Labels above bars:** only show a % label when `pct >= 10` to avoid
  collision with adjacent labels at small values. Truncate to integer; the
  "%" suffix is enough context.

## Layout

- **Card pattern:** one Window owns a `card_layer` (full bounds) + a thin
  `indicator_layer` for the page dots. Each card is a single `CardDrawFn`
  function — no per-card lifecycle. Switching cards = `layer_mark_dirty`. This
  was simpler and faster than per-card layer trees.
- **Active page-indicator pill** = 16w × 4h, radius 2. Inactive dots = 4×4.
  Gap = 6. Centered horizontally. Cleaner than 5 equal-size dots.
- **Symmetric horizontal margins are critical.** Define a single `UI_MARGIN_X`
  constant (`PBL_IF_ROUND_ELSE(20, 12)`) and apply it to every left AND right
  gutter on every card. Without this, cards look off-center because "left margin
  = right margin" was not enforced and visual balance breaks when font sizes
  change. A single constant guarantees consistency across all screens.
- **Use constants for all shared layout values.** `UI_HEADER_Y`,
  `UI_HEADER_HEIGHT`, `UI_MARGIN_X` in a shared `ui.h` — then every card can
  position its content body at `header_y + UI_HEADER_HEIGHT + gap` without
  hardcoding offsets that drift when you resize the header font.
- **Header icon sizing matters.** A 20px icon next to `GOTHIC_18_BOLD` text is
  slightly tight; 22–24px feels natural. Pass `icon_size` as a parameter to
  the icon draw function rather than hardcoding in each card.
- **Round display top padding:** round has significantly more wasted corners,
  so `UI_HEADER_Y` should be ~24 vs ~8 on rect. Same rule applies to the page
  indicator and bottom banners — `pad_bottom = PBL_IF_ROUND_ELSE(40, 22)`.
- **Rain banner** at bottom of card 0: orange pill, `banner_h=22`,
  `banner_w=PBL_IF_ROUND_ELSE(130,140)`, `pad_bottom=PBL_IF_ROUND_ELSE(40,22)`.
  The round needs more bottom padding to clear the bezel.
- **Rotating status banner:** to show two messages in the same screen slot
  (e.g. "RAIN IN 15MIN" and "UPDATED 3M AGO") without extra space, flip between
  them using the animation tick counter: `if (frame % 40 < 20) { show A } else
  { show B }`. At 100ms/frame, that's a 2s on / 2s off cycle — readable.
  Only redraw on the transition frame to avoid unnecessary CPU: `if (frame % 20 == 0) nav_redraw()`.
- **Fonts in stock SDK** that worked well:
  - `FONT_KEY_LECO_42_NUMBERS` — big temperature digits
  - `FONT_KEY_GOTHIC_18_BOLD` — Hi/Lo, headers, wind/humidity labels
  - `FONT_KEY_GOTHIC_28_BOLD` — sunrise/sunset times
  - `FONT_KEY_GOTHIC_14_BOLD` — bar-chart hour labels, secondary info

## AppMessage / PKJS / Clay

- **Declare every key** in `package.json` `messageKeys`. The build generates
  `MESSAGE_KEY_*` C macros automatically — no manual numbering.
- **`app_message_open(1024, 256)`** — round up the inbox to fit the largest
  bundle (we send ~22 keys at once for full weather).
- **Never `strncpy(dst, t->value->cstring, sizeof(dst))` without manually
  zero-terminating** — `strncpy` does NOT null-terminate when the source is
  longer than `n`. Always:
  ```c
  strncpy(d->wind_dir, t->value->cstring, sizeof(d->wind_dir) - 1);
  d->wind_dir[sizeof(d->wind_dir) - 1] = '\0';
  ```
- **Persist cache.** Save `WeatherData` struct as a single blob via
  `persist_write_data(KEY, &data, sizeof(data))` so the watch shows last-known
  values immediately on launch instead of empty fields while PKJS fetches.
- **CRITICAL: Bump persist key when struct layout changes.** If you add,
  remove, or reorder any field in a persisted struct, the old blob on disk will
  be deserialized with misaligned fields — silent corruption. Increment the
  `PERSIST_KEY_WEATHER` constant by 1 any time the struct changes. The stale
  blob is silently ignored (persist_read returns 0), so the app falls back to
  zeroed/default values and re-fetches cleanly.
- **Clay v2** (`@rebble/clay` package, install via `pebble package install`):
  - `new Clay(config, null, { autoHandleEvents: false })` if you need a custom
    `webviewclosed` flow (we did, to persist `units` to localStorage *and*
    forward to the watch).
  - `clay.getSettings(e.response, false)` returns the raw key/value object;
    `clay.getSettings(e.response)` returns a watch-ready dict for
    `Pebble.sendAppMessage`.
- **Clay radiogroup string values come as `TUPLE_CSTRING`, not `TUPLE_INT`.**
  If you put `value: "0"` / `value: "1"` in your Clay config (which is the
  norm), the AppMessage tuple arrives with `t->type == TUPLE_CSTRING` and
  the value is in `t->value->cstring`. Reading `t->value->int32` silently
  returns 0 — which is why "Dark" never seemed to apply. Handle both:
  ```c
  int v = (t->type == TUPLE_CSTRING) ? atoi(t->value->cstring)
                                     : (int)t->value->int32;
  ```
  Also note `t->value->cstring` is a flexible array member (`char cstring[0]`),
  so `&& t->value->cstring` is a `-Werror=address` warning under
  arm-none-eabi-gcc 14 ("comparison of address of flexible array will always
  evaluate to true"). Drop the null check entirely — flexible array members
  can't be null.
- **Theme / dark mode window update:** applying a new background color only to
  the window doesn't automatically redraw it. Keep a static `Window *` in
  `theme.c` and call both `window_set_background_color` AND
  `layer_mark_dirty(window_get_root_layer(win))` from `theme_set`. Register the
  window once via `theme_apply_to_window(win)` in `prv_window_load`. This
  ensures SELECT (or Clay config) instantly repaints without extra wiring in
  every callsite.
- **Open-Meteo** is a free, no-API-key weather source. Combine
  `/v1/forecast` (current + hourly + daily) with `/v1/air-quality` for AQI.
  Use `temperature_unit` and `wind_speed_unit` query params for unit handling
  rather than converting client-side.
- **Geolocation** in PKJS: `navigator.geolocation.getCurrentPosition` works in
  the simulator (returns SF coords) and on real phones. Always provide a
  fallback location for when the user denies permission.
- **Open-Meteo `forecast_hours=N`** does NOT slice the hourly array starting
  at the current hour the way the docs imply when combined with
  `forecast_days`. Safer pattern: fetch `forecast_days=2` (so you have a
  full day's worth even at 11pm), then walk `hourly.time[]` to find an
  entry matching `YYYY-MM-DDTHH:00` for the current hour and slice from
  there. Otherwise the precip bars start at midnight.
- **"Last updated" timestamp:** the most reliable approach is to have the PKJS
  side send `Date.now() / 1000` (unix seconds) as an AppMessage key
  (`LastUpdated`). On the C side, store it in `WeatherData.last_updated`
  (uint32_t). Then display `(time(NULL) - last_updated) / 60` minutes elapsed
  in a status banner. Persists across restarts automatically since it's in the
  cached blob.

## Animation

- **`app_timer_register(ms, cb, ctx)`** is the simplest periodic animation
  primitive. Re-register from inside the callback for a repeating timer.
- **Only redraw when the animated card is visible.** Saved CPU and battery —
  guard with `if (nav_current_index() == 0) nav_redraw();`. The other 4 cards
  are static, so they cost nothing.
- **100ms frame rate** is plenty smooth for primitive-drawn icons and easy on
  the battery. Anything faster wastes power.
- **Animate offsets, not whole frames.** Sin-bob via `sin_lookup` against a
  short cyclic counter (e.g. `frame % 32`) is cheap and looks natural.
- **Refresh-on-open via delayed timer.** Don't call `comm_request_refresh()`
  synchronously in `prv_window_load` — the AppMessage channel isn't fully
  ready that early. Register a 750ms one-shot timer instead:
  ```c
  app_timer_register(750, prv_initial_refresh, NULL);
  ```
  This gives the window time to fully paint before the JS side wakes up.
- **Touch gestures (pull-down to refresh):** track `(start_x, start_y)` on
  `TouchEvent_Touchdown`, then on `TouchEvent_Liftoff` compute
  `dx = x - start_x`, `dy = y - start_y`. Treat it as a downward swipe if
  `dy > 60 && abs(dy) > abs(dx)`. Horizontal threshold ~30px prevents false
  fires on diagonal swipes. No SDK helper for this — build it yourself.

## Build / project

- **Glob source files** in `wscript` (default Pebble template already does):
  `ctx.path.ant_glob('src/c/**/*.c')`. Adding a new card = drop a `.c` in
  `src/c/cards/` and `nav_register` it. No wscript edits needed.
- **`#pragma once`** works fine across all targets — no need for include
  guards.
- **`PBL_IF_ROUND_ELSE`** evaluates at compile time per target. The same
  source file is compiled twice (once per platform); don't worry about
  runtime branching cost.
- **`watchapp.watchface=false`** in package.json makes it an app (back button
  exits). Default scaffold is `true` (watchface).
- **`capabilities: ["configurable"]`** is required for Clay to even appear in
  the phone app's settings menu.

## Misc gotchas

- **`pebble screenshot` blocks indefinitely** if the emulator's pypkjs proxy
  has died but qemu is still running. Symptom: command never returns.
  Workaround: kill both processes and reinstall.
- **Pebble's compiler is `arm-none-eabi-gcc 14.2.1`.** Standard C99/C11. No
  `<stdbool.h>` issues but watch out for VLA usage on small stacks.
- **App memory cap:** 128 KB total RAM. We finished at ~10 KB footprint with
  120 KB free heap — room to spare for animated APNG resources or larger
  caches.
- **Resources cap:** 256 KB pbpack, 256 resource entries. APNG hero icons
  would fit easily but we ended up not needing them since primitives looked
  great and animate cheaper.

## Things that *didn't* work / dead ends

- Tried `pebble emu-app-config` — Python traceback in this tool version.
  Skipped, used hardware Clay flow.
- `forecast_hours=5` to get next-5-hour precip forecast — seemed right but
  returns an array starting at midnight, not the current hour. Replaced with
  `forecast_days=2` + manual time-array walk (see AppMessage / PKJS section).
- Applying a minimum bar height (e.g. 4% floor) to bar charts so all bars are
  always visible — creates phantom bars for 0% rain probability, making the
  chart look wrong on clear days. Use a 2px muted baseline stroke for true
  zero values instead.
- Wiring theme to `window_set_background_color` alone without `layer_mark_dirty`
  — old background shows until next redraw event. Must force redraw immediately.
- Null-checking `t->value->cstring` before calling `atoi` — causes a
  `-Werror=address` build failure under gcc 14 (flexible array member address
  is never null by definition). Just call `atoi` directly.
- Tried drawing half-suns by stacking a filled circle + a white-filled rect to
  mask the bottom half. Looked OK in light mode, broken in dark mode. Use
  `graphics_fill_radial` from -90° to +90° instead.
- Tried original `draw_chevron` helper — produced Y-shaped arrows. Replaced
  with explicit shaft + two arm lines.
- Tried `pebble kill` to fix stuck emulator — usually has no effect. `pkill -9`
  the qemu-pebble and pypkjs processes by name instead.
- Tried backgrounding `pebble install` inside an `&&` chain — emulator dies
  when the wrapper exits. Always use `nohup ... & disown`.
